  Now I see the bug. In the \`handleSearch\` function (line 868-871), the \`focusIndex\` is calculated as the index of the first visible match. But the issue is that \`Array.findIndex\` returns \`-1\` when no match is found, not \`null\`. The \`?? null\` on line 871 won't convert \`-1\` to \`null\` since \`-1\` is not nullish.

  But the main bug described is: when the user navigates to a later match (e.g., match 5 out of 10) and then changes the query so fewer matches remain (e.g., only 3), the focus index stays at 5 which is out of bounds.


  The \`onChange\` handler triggers \`handleSearch\`, which computes a new \`focusIndex\` based on the updated matches, but the real issue is that \`focusIndex\` becomes stale when the number of matches decreases. So the real issue is that \`handleSearch\` is debounced at 350ms, which means there's a window where \`isSearching\` is true but the focus index hasn't been recalculated yet. During that delay, if the user has fewer matches than before, the old \`focusIndex\` could be pointing to an index that no longer exists in the new results. The effect on line 101 doesn't reset the focus index when the scene changes, which is fine since that's for scene updates. But when the user changes the query, the \`onChange\` handler calls the debounced search while setting \`isSearching\` to true, which causes the effect to bail out early. After the debounce completes, the search runs but I need to trace through what happens to the focus index at that point.

  After the debounced handler fires, it sets the focus index based on \`findIndex\` looking for the first visible match. The issue is that \`findIndex\` returns \`-1\` when nothing matches, and since \`-1\` isn't nullish, the nullish coalescing operator doesn't catch it—so the focus index gets set to \`-1\` instead of a safe value. This becomes a problem when the user navigates to a later match and then changes the query, leaving the focus pointing at an invalid index. I see the issue now—when the search query changes and produces fewer matches, the \`findIndex\` returns \`-1\` if none of the previously visible matches are still in the new set, leaving \`focusIndex\` pointing to an invalid index. The solution is to reset focus to the first match (index 0) whenever matches exist but the current focus index becomes invalid.

