  Now I understand the bug clearly. Let me look at the \`handleSearch\` function's focusIndex calculation:

  \`\`\`js
  const focusIndex =
      matchItems.findIndex((matchItem) =>
        visibleIds.has(matchItem.element.id),
      ) ?? null;
  \`\`\`

  \`Array.findIndex\` returns \`-1\` when no match is found, and \`-1 ?? null\` is \`-1\` (not nullish). So \`focusIndex\` can be \`-1\`.

  But more importantly, the bug the user describes: navigating to a later match (e.g., index 4), then changing query to have fewer matches (e.g., 3).

  I'm tracing through the \`onChange\` handler to see how the focus index gets recalculated when the search query changes. The handler sets the input value, triggers the search, and passes a callback that updates the search matches state...

  Actually, I think I see the potential race condition now. When the user types quickly, \`onChange\` fires multiple times, but since \`handleSearch\` is debounced, only the final call executes. In the meantime, the component re-renders with \`isSearching\` set to true, but the old \`focusIndex\` and \`searchMatches\` remain in state until the debounced callback finally fires and updates them.

  The issue is that \`findIndex\` might return \`-1\` if no match is found, and the nullish coalescing operator doesn't catch that case. But there's also another path through the \`useEffect\` that checks whether the search query has actually changed compared to what was previously searched.

  When the scene nonce changes or the query differs from what's stored in the ref, the effect calls \`handleSearch\` with a callback that updates the search matches and app state, but crucially it never calls \`setFocusIndex\`. So when the search reruns due to scene changes while not actively searching, the focus index stays wherever it was. And once \`isSearching\` becomes \`false\` after the debounce completes, if the query hasn't changed since the last search, the effect won't trigger again to reset the focus.

  But I think the real issue is more straightforward. When a user searches for "test" and navigates to index 3, then changes the query to "testing" which only has 2 matches, the \`handleSearch\` callback fires with the new matches and calls \`setFocusIndex\` with whatever \`findIndex\` returns. If \`findIndex\` can't find a visible item, it returns -1, which doesn't get caught by the null check, leaving focusIndex at -1 and breaking the search navigation.

  The fix is straightforward: when \`findIndex\` returns -1 but there are matches available, default to index 0 instead. Let me update the \`handleSearch\` function and add a test to verify this works.
